The essential and usual one handed listing aliases:<p><pre><code>  alias l=&#x27;ls -laFT&#x27;
  alias ll=&#x27;ls -1aF&#x27;
  alias k=&#x27;ls -laFTrt&#x27;
  alias kk=&#x27;ls -1aFrt&#x27;
</code></pre>
Some X + tee magic for logging.<p><pre><code>  alias xlog=&#x27;mv .xlog.txt .xlog.txt.old && startx -- -nolisten tcp 2>&1 | tee . xlog.txt > /dev/console&#x27;

  alias xdbg=&#x27;mv .xdbg.txt .xdbg.txt.old && startx -- /usr/X11R6/bin/X -keepPriv 2>&1 | tee .xdbg.txt > /dev/console&#x27;
</code></pre>
And in ~/.xinitrc run an oddly colored xterm with /dev/console output:<p><pre><code>  xterm -C -fg &#x27;#b00020&#x27; -geometry 80x38+0+0 &
</code></pre>
Most folks don&#x27;t start X manually but when working on X itself, extra logging can often help.
